
@startuml

' Define classes and their attributes

class Provider {
    - name: String
    - location: String
}

class Cruise {
    - cruiseNumber: Integer
    - name: String
    - startDate: Date
    - endDate: Date
    - destinationArea: DestinationArea
}

class Employee {
    - name: String
    - socialSecurityNumber: String
}

class Guest {
    - name: String
    - isVIP: Boolean
}

class Ship {
    - name: String
    - numberOfDecks: Integer
    - length: Double
    - maxPassengers: Integer
}

class TravelAgency {
    - name: String
    - address: String
}

class Booking {
    - bookingNumber: String
    - bookingDate: Date
}

class DestinationArea {
    - name: String
    - seaName: String
}

class Show {
    - title: String
    - duration: Integer // in minutes
}

class Ticket {
    - cruise: Cruise
    - guest: Guest
}

' Relationships

Provider "1" -- "0..*" Cruise : organizes
Cruise "1" -- "1" Ship : uses
Cruise "1" -- "0..*" Employee : employs
Cruise "1" -- "0..*" Guest : has participants
Cruise "1" -- "0..*" Show : offers
Cruise "1" -- "1" DestinationArea : heads to
TravelAgency "1" -- "0..*" Booking : creates
Booking "1" -- "1" Cruise : for
Booking "1" -- "1" Guest : by
Guest "1" -- "0..*" Ticket : owns
Ticket "1" -- "1" Cruise : belongs to

' Unidirectional associations (no return arrow)

Guest "0..*" --> "1" Cruise : participates in
Cruise "1" --> "0..*" Ticket : issues

@enduml

---

### Explanation of Key Points:

- **One-to-many** relationships are indicated with `0..*`.
- **Mandatory one** is shown as `1`.
- Each class includes only relevant attributes.
- The `Ticket` class ensures that a guest can have multiple tickets but only **one ticket per cruise**, and each ticket is linked to exactly one cruise.

